            ]
        },
        {
            "type": "title",
            "content": {
                "title_content": [
                    {
                        "type": "text",
                        "content": "Abstract "
                    }
                ],
                "level": 1
            },
            "bbox": [
                256,
                186,
                321,
                201
            ]
        },
        {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": {
                "paragraph_content": [
                    {
                        "type": "text",
                        "content": "This paper describes a fully-differential CMOS readout circuit for silicon micro-resonant accelerometer. Tested with a SOI resonator, the readout chip sustains the oscillation at  "
                    },
                    {
                        "type": "equation_inline",
                        "content": "110\\mathrm{kHz}"
                    },
                    {
                        "type": "text",
                        "content": " with a phase noise of  "
                    },
                    {
                        "type": "equation_inline",
                        "content": "-36\\mathrm{dBc}@\\mathrm{Hz}"
                    },
                    {
                        "type": "text",
                        "content": " and a bias stability of  "
                    },
                    {
                        "type": "equation_inline",
                        "content": "0.0035\\mathrm{Hz}"
                    },
                    {
                        "type": "text",
                        "content": " or  "
                    },
                    {
                        "type": "equation_inline",
                        "content": "32\\mathrm{ppb}"
                    },
                    {
                        "type": "text",
                        "content": ", which can be translated to an amplitude noise of  "
                    },
                    {
                        "type": "equation_inline",
                        "content": "1\\mathrm{A} / \\sqrt{Hz}"
                    },
                    {
                        "type": "text",
                        "content": " down to  "
                    },
                    {
                        "type": "equation_inline",
                        "content": "0.05\\mathrm{Hz}"
                    },
                    {
                        "type": "text",
                        "content": " and stability of  "
                    },
                    {
                        "type": "equation_inline",
                        "content": "0.22\\mathrm{A}"
                    },
                    {
                        "type": "text",
                        "content": " up to 100 seconds. The chip is fabricated in a  "
                    },
                    {
                        "type": "equation_inline",
                        "content": "0.35\\mathrm{-um}"
                    },
                    {
                        "type": "text",
                        "content": " CMOS process and draws  "
                    },
                    {
                        "type": "equation_inline",
                        "content": "5\\mathrm{mA}"
                    },
                    {
                        "type": "text",
                        "content": " under a  "
                    },
                    {
                        "type": "equation_inline",
                        "content": "3.3\\mathrm{-V}"
                    },
                    {
                        "type": "text",
                        "content": " single supply. "
                    }
                ]
            },
            "bbox": [
                86,
                214,
                491,
                328
            ]
        },
        {
            "type": "title",
            "content": {
                "title_content": [
                    {
                        "type": "text",
                        "content": "Key words: MEMS resonator, CMOS readout circuit, bias stability "
                    }
                ],
                "level": 1
            },
            "bbox": [
                86,
                339,
                491,
                369
            ]
        },
        {
            "type": "title",
            "content": {
                "title_content": [
                    {
                        "type": "text",
                        "content": "Introduction "
                    }
                ],
                "level": 1
            },
            "bbox": [
                243,
                380,
                336,
                395
            ]
        },
        {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": {
                "paragraph_content": [
                    {
                        "type": "text",
                        "content": "Aerospace and inertial navigation set a very stringent requirement on the precision of accelerometer. This precision is determined by noise figure and more importantly by bias stability, which is defined as the offset variation during the subsequent period after calibration. Bias stabilities ranging from 30ppb [1] to 5ppb [2] were demonstrated in silicon resonant accelerometers (SRA) with readout circuits made from discrete components. The bias instability is caused by the interaction between flicker noise and the resonator's nonlinearity. Due to the strong flicker noise associated with MOS devices, it is challenging to meet the stability requirement using CMOS technology. The only CMOS readout circuit [3] ever reported for SRA has a 220ppb bias stability despite that a separate 16-V power supply is used to bias the resonator. In this paper, a low-noise, low drift CMOS readout circuit for SRA is presented. The chip and the sense resonator operate with a single 3.3-V supply. Several techniques are proposed to suppress the flicker noises and reduce their interactions with the strong mechanical nonlinearity due to the increased oscillation amplitude to maintain the same SNR under reduced bias voltage. The "
                    }
                ]
            },
            "bbox": [
                86,
                407,
                491,
                710
            ]
        },
        {
            "type": "image",
            "content": {
                "image_source": {
                    "path": "images/8ea7769676fc5f7bef49c7789d3e59c79a7f39153927a9deedd0cf14a64a5252.jpg"
                },
                "image_caption": [],
                "image_footnote": []
            },
            "bbox": [
                76,
                711,
                274,
                818
            ]
        },
        {
            "type": "image",
            "content": {
                "image_source": {
                    "path": "images/ef85af370dd0947671d47ad5f0f0b7e2ffc9462521c0b2773bfbf25a1fa57830.jpg"
                },
                "image_caption": [
                    {
                        "type": "text",
                        "content": "Fig.1 Typical DETF resonator (a) and our sense resonator (b) "
                    }
                ],
                "image_footnote": []
            },
            "bbox": [
                276,
                711,
                485,
                818
            ]
        },
        {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": {
                "paragraph_content": [
                    {
                        "type": "text",
                        "content": "fabricated chip, tested with a SOI resonator, has achieved superior bias stability of 32 ppb. "
                    }
                ]
            },
            "bbox": [
                516,
                186,
                921,
                217
            ]
        },
        {
            "type": "title",
            "content": {
                "title_content": [
                    {
                        "type": "text",
                        "content": "Sense Resonator "
                    }
                ],
                "level": 1
            },
            "bbox": [
                660,
                231,
                779,
                244
            ]
        },
        {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": {
                "paragraph_content": [
                    {
                        "type": "text",
                        "content": "In the previous works [1-3], the sense resonators were made out of the double-ended tuning fork (DETF) structure shown in Fig.1.(a). The beams were excited exactly  "
                    },
                    {
                        "type": "equation_inline",
                        "content": "180^{\\circ}"
                    },
                    {
                        "type": "text",
                        "content": " out-of-phase to minimize the acoustic radiation. Although this structure helps achieve high quality factor (Q), it favors only single-ended operation. In our design, to take advantage of differential operation, a connection is made at the center of DETF, as shown in Fig.1(b), which forces both beams to move exactly in-phase, resulting a differential capacitance change. Sense and drive operation share the same electrodes at different timeslots. The resonator is biased with a 3.3-6.4V pulse generated by an on-chip charge pump. The bootstrap pulse bias triples the feedback force and generates charge outputs for the sense interface. A  "
                    },
                    {
                        "type": "equation_inline",
                        "content": "110\\mathrm{-kHz}"
                    },
                    {
                        "type": "text",
                        "content": " sense resonator is fabricated from the top layer of the SOI wafer using SOIMUMPS process. "
                    }
                ]
            },
            "bbox": [
                514,
                258,
                921,
                479
            ]
        },
        {
            "type": "title",
            "content": {
                "title_content": [
                    {
                        "type": "text",
                        "content": "System overview "
                    }
                ],
                "level": 1
            },
            "bbox": [
                658,
                492,
                779,
                507
            ]
        },
        {
            "type": "image",
            "content": {
                "image_source": {
                    "path": "images/c0ff590a6daf3e9ffc59fdbd03be9aa3b25943f5f6a097b40b6e8691087cbe99.jpg"
                },
                "image_caption": [
                    {
                        "type": "text",
                        "content": "Fig.2(a) shows the overall system block diagram. The displacement of resonant beam is detected with a low noise sense interface circuit. Velocity signal is obtained by the differentiator,  "
                    },
                    {
                        "type": "equation_inline",
                        "content": "\\mathrm{A}_1(1 - z^{-1})"
                    },
                    {
                        "type": "text",
                        "content": ", and further amplified by the variable "
                    }
                ],
                "image_footnote": []
            },
            "bbox": [
                527,
                584,
                916,
                678
            ]
        },
        {
            "type": "image",
            "content": {
                "image_source": {
                    "path": "images/45cd3435bc69d4693aa6fa1cb68f92ee0ef83d5865ff797c51edc2042be6f300.jpg"
                },
                "image_caption": [
                    {
                        "type": "text",
                        "content": "Fig.2 System schematic diagram (a) and implemented system with CMOS readout circuit and resonator wire-bonded together (b) "
                    }
                ],
                "image_footnote": []
            },
            "bbox": [
