        {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": {
                "paragraph_content": [
                    {
                        "type": "text",
                        "content": "gain amplifier (VGA). It is then fed back and drives the same electrodes, through a buffer, in different timeslots to generate electrostatic force. The gain of VGA is automatically set by a control loop. Inside the control loop, the amplitude is detected with a full-wave rectifier and compared with a preset value  "
                    },
                    {
                        "type": "equation_inline",
                        "content": "V_{R0}"
                    },
                    {
                        "type": "text",
                        "content": ". The resultant error signal is fed to a loop filter  "
                    },
                    {
                        "type": "equation_inline",
                        "content": "L(s)"
                    },
                    {
                        "type": "text",
                        "content": " whose output controls VGA gain. "
                    }
                ]
            },
            "bbox": [
                83,
                59,
                482,
                159
            ]
        },
        {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": {
                "paragraph_content": [
                    {
                        "type": "text",
                        "content": "The flicker noise in the oscillation amplitude of nonlinear resonator translates into bias instability or  "
                    },
                    {
                        "type": "equation_inline",
                        "content": "1 / f^3"
                    },
                    {
                        "type": "text",
                        "content": " phase noise. Therefore, reducing the flicker noise in the oscillation amplitude is the primary design target. To do so, the flicker noises in the full-wave rectifier and loop filter are removed by two sets of choppers, respectively. While the amplitude modulation of the flick noise in the VGA is suppressed by a  "
                    },
                    {
                        "type": "equation_inline",
                        "content": "2^{\\mathrm{nd}}"
                    },
                    {
                        "type": "text",
                        "content": " order loop filter  "
                    },
                    {
                        "type": "equation_inline",
                        "content": "\\mathrm{L(s)}"
                    },
                    {
                        "type": "text",
                        "content": ". "
                    }
                ]
            },
            "bbox": [
                83,
                161,
                482,
                275
            ]
        },
        {
            "type": "title",
            "content": {
                "title_content": [
                    {
                        "type": "text",
                        "content": "Key circuit block implementation "
                    }
                ],
                "level": 1
            },
            "bbox": [
                171,
                291,
                395,
                305
            ]
        },
        {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": {
                "paragraph_content": [
                    {
                        "type": "text",
                        "content": "The sense capacitance  "
                    },
                    {
                        "type": "equation_inline",
                        "content": "C_s"
                    },
                    {
                        "type": "text",
                        "content": " and the capacitance variation  "
                    },
                    {
                        "type": "equation_inline",
                        "content": "\\Delta C_s"
                    },
                    {
                        "type": "text",
                        "content": " are 20fF and 0.5fF, respectively. A capacitive sense interface circuit in [4] without the input common-mode feedback is adopted in this design. The interface is isolated from resonator with a pair of decoupling capacitors to avoid overdriving the opamp during the feedback timeslot. The signal is sampled at a rate of 5MHz with multi-phase clock [4]. NMOS input telescopic OTA with passive feed-forward capacitor is chosen for the best power-noise-speed tradeoff. "
                    }
                ]
            },
            "bbox": [
                83,
                319,
                482,
                448
            ]
        },
        {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": {
                "paragraph_content": [
                    {
                        "type": "text",
                        "content": "The differentiator is realized by charge redistribution among three capacitors. C1 stores the present value while C2 and C3 alternate store the delayed value. This switch-cap network was combined with an offset-free gain stage to obtain enough amplification and reject undesirable DC offset. A differential pair amplifier (M1, M2) provides a continuous output (Fig.3.a). "
                    }
                ]
            },
            "bbox": [
                83,
                449,
                482,
                548
            ]
        },
        {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": {
                "paragraph_content": [
                    {
                        "type": "text",
                        "content": "A pair of NMOS full-wave rectifiers is used to detect the oscillation amplitude. Two sets of Choppers are employed for "
                    }
                ]
            },
            "bbox": [
                84,
                550,
                482,
                578
            ]
        },
        {
            "type": "image",
            "content": {
                "image_source": {
                    "path": "images/19630d2497cb6c014d43ca8962092ad9934d37ce6c47a121d9ab8caf98d14663.jpg"
                },
                "image_caption": [],
                "image_footnote": []
            },
            "bbox": [
                96,
                584,
                478,
                738
            ]
        },
        {
            "type": "image",
            "content": {
                "image_source": {
                    "path": "images/91c458aa521a558ad0e18cf76fb89eb9edf86e0d21aed5dd3b05ca5fe33d9632.jpg"
                },
                "image_caption": [
                    {
                        "type": "text",
                        "content": "(a) "
                    },
                    {
                        "type": "text",
                        "content": "(b) "
                    },
                    {
                        "type": "text",
                        "content": "Fig.3. Circuit diagrams of (a) differentiator and (b) chopped rectifier and Gm cells in amplitude control loop. "
                    }
                ],
                "image_footnote": []
            },
            "bbox": [
                94,
                749,
                468,
                855
            ]
        },
        {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": {
                "paragraph_content": [
                    {
                        "type": "text",
                        "content": "the rectifiers and the Gm cells in loop filter so that the flicker noise can also be removed, as shown in Fig.3(b). "
                    }
                ]
            },
            "bbox": [
                514,
                61,
                911,
                87
            ]
        },
        {
            "type": "title",
            "content": {
                "title_content": [
                    {
                        "type": "text",
                        "content": "Experiment result and discussion "
                    }
                ],
                "level": 1
            },
            "bbox": [
                602,
                103,
                825,
                117
            ]
        },
        {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": {
                "paragraph_content": [
                    {
                        "type": "text",
                        "content": "The resonator chip and CMOS IC chip are mounted on a PCB and wire-bonded together (Fig2.b). The PCB is placed in a  "
                    },
                    {
                        "type": "equation_inline",
                        "content": "125\\mathrm{Pa}"
                    },
                    {
                        "type": "text",
                        "content": " vacuum environment. The oscillation signal is taken from the output of the VGA and drives a full-customized PLL with a frequency ratio of 420. The frequency is recorded with Agilent E53131A and filtered with a  "
                    },
                    {
                        "type": "equation_inline",
                        "content": "0.0005\\mathrm{-Hz}"
                    },
                    {
                        "type": "text",
                        "content": " high-pass filter to compensate the temperature effect. The Allan variances of compensated data are plotted in Fig.4. The floor of the variance plot is known as the bias stability. The chip design allows us to disable the chopper and to replace the  "
                    },
                    {
                        "type": "equation_inline",
                        "content": "2^{\\mathrm{nd}}"
                    },
                    {
                        "type": "text",
                        "content": " order loop filter  "
                    },
                    {
                        "type": "equation_inline",
                        "content": "\\mathrm{L(s)}"
                    },
                    {
                        "type": "text",
                        "content": " with a  "
                    },
                    {
                        "type": "equation_inline",
                        "content": "1^{\\mathrm{st}}"
                    },
                    {
                        "type": "text",
                        "content": " order one to compare their respective effects on stability performance. The efficiency of "
                    }
                ]
            },
            "bbox": [
                514,
                131,
                911,
                296
            ]
        },
        {
            "type": "image",
            "content": {
                "image_source": {
                    "path": "images/31cbe89cda28d7a849b3157230251856c6f70b2045eab4a266bf9845bad3af2a.jpg"
                },
                "image_caption": [
                    {
                        "type": "text",
                        "content": "Fig.4. Measured Allan variance. "
                    }
                ],
                "image_footnote": []
            },
            "bbox": [
                529,
                313,
                883,
                465
            ]
        },
        {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": {
                "paragraph_content": [
                    {
                        "type": "text",
                        "content": "chopper can be clearly seen. But the flicker noise was not completely removed even with the  "
                    },
                    {
                        "type": "equation_inline",
                        "content": "2^{\\mathrm{nd}}"
                    },
                    {
                        "type": "text",
                        "content": " order loop control filter. The residue flicker noise was found to be caused by the flicker noise in  "
                    },
                    {
                        "type": "equation_inline",
                        "content": "\\mathbf{M}_3"
                    },
                    {
                        "type": "text",
                        "content": " (Fig.3.a) which modulates gain of the differential stage. "
                    }
                ]
            },
            "bbox": [
                514,
                494,
                911,
                562
            ]
        },
        {
            "type": "title",
            "content": {
                "title_content": [
                    {
                        "type": "text",
                        "content": "Conclusion "
                    }
                ],
                "level": 1
            },
            "bbox": [
                674,
                577,
                751,
                589
            ]
        },
        {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": {
                "paragraph_content": [
                    {
                        "type": "text",
                        "content": "A fully-differential CMOS readout circuit with 3.3-V single supply for silicon resonant accelerometer has been implemented and achieved the stability of  "
                    },
                    {
                        "type": "equation_inline",
                        "content": "32\\mathrm{ppb}"
                    },
                    {
                        "type": "text",
                        "content": ". Chopper technique and high-order loop filter were proposed for amplitude control to improve the bias stability and experimentally verified. "
                    }
                ]
            },
            "bbox": [
                514,
                604,
                911,
                684
            ]
        },
